organizing multiple musicians

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:52.650
and multiple instruments,
and paying them and getting them into

00:02:52.650 --> 00:02:56.620
one room where we can actually go ahead
and experiment with textures and sounds

00:02:56.630 --> 00:02:59.970
that are beyond what a particular
band have within their players.

00:03:01.420 --> 00:03:02.350
And so that's been quite expensive.

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:06.100
And so, some musical instruments
is definitely something the

00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:09.410
computer has helped us with.

00:03:09.410 --> 00:03:11.920
It has given us much more of a
palette of tools to work with.

00:03:12.580 --> 00:03:15.310
So that's the musical aspect,
the musical instrument aspect of it.

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:16.840
The next one, microphones.

00:03:16.840 --> 00:03:19.830
Now we need microphones in the
recording studio to help us get down

00:03:19.900 --> 00:03:21.930
the sound of these acoustic instruments.

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:24.980
We've got an acoustic guitar,
we need to mic it up.

00:03:24.980 --> 00:03:27.470
That microphone gets plugged
into a mixing console,

00:03:27.470 --> 00:03:30.090
and then straight on to
the multi-track recorder.

00:03:31.420 --> 00:03:33.380
So let's talk about mixing consoles.

00:03:33.380 --> 00:03:38.060
Now the mixing console is inherently
there to pre-amplify the microphones or

00:03:38.070 --> 00:03:40.410
the line instruments that we plug in.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:45.140
It allows us to boost that signal,
add some equalization,

00:03:45.150 --> 00:03:49.870
and then that will often go off and be
recorded on the multi-track recorder.

00:03:50.910 --> 00:03:53.080
Now mixing consoles range in size.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:03:56.580
They can go from anywhere from
a four-channel mixing device

00:03:56.580 --> 00:04:00.140
all the way up to something
like a 96-input SSL like that,

00:04:01.010 --> 00:04:03.870
which could essentially
cost a million dollars plus.

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:08.170
Now the other nice thing about
the mixing console is it allows

00:04:08.170 --> 00:04:11.150
us to take all of the tracks
coming back from the multi-track

00:04:11.300 --> 00:04:12.620
so that we can listen to playback.

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:17.180
So we can mix and we can balance out that
and we can listen to the arrangement and

00:04:17.180 --> 00:04:21.610
see exactly which musician's parts need
to be replaced with real musician parts.

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:25.900
So essentially that's the
idea of the mixing console.

00:04:25.900 --> 00:04:27.860
And as I said, they can be very,
very expensive.

00:04:27.860 --> 00:04:31.760
And a lot of them, like the SSL,
on Each of their channels,

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:34.720
they'll have a dynamic section
like a noise gate and a compressor.

00:04:34.860 --> 00:04:39.230
And they'll usually have a center
master section that allows you

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:45.590
total control over the volume
of your speakers in the studio.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:50.590
So, if I can get a new battery for this,
this would be great.

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:52.000
There we go.

00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:53.060
Multi-track recorders.

00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:55.500
Now, after everything's gone
through the mixing console,

00:04:55.500 --> 00:04:58.100
it's going to go on to
the multi-track recorder.

00:04:58.100 --> 00:05:00.370
A multi-track recorder is
a little bit like the tape

00:05:00.710 --> 00:05:02.040
player that you have at home.

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:05.050
I don't have any tape
players at home anymore,

00:05:05.050 --> 00:05:06.990
but use your imagination.

00:05:07.030 --> 00:05:11.120
One exception is a lot bigger, of course,
and a lot more expensive.

00:05:11.120 --> 00:05:14.570
But the thing about a multi-track,
it allows every instrument

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:15.850
to have its own track.

00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:21.760
It allows us to stack and layer different
instruments onto the multi-tape recorder.

