00:06:02.790 --> 00:06:06.600
And in the early part of the 90s,
when digital multi-tracks first

00:06:06.790 --> 00:06:10.180
started appearing on the market,
we then had single machines

00:06:10.180 --> 00:06:13.530
that could get as high as 48
tracks per single machine.

00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:15.500
So that's a multi-track recorder.

00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:17.850
Now,
when you've done all of your recording

00:06:17.850 --> 00:06:20.540
and everything's sounding good,
we usually go into what

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:22.910
we call the mixing stage,
and this allows us to

00:06:22.990 --> 00:06:24.640
take effects processors.

00:06:24.780 --> 00:06:27.630
And effects processors can run
the gamut of different types.

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:31.860
They can range from subtle
things to things that radically

00:06:31.940 --> 00:06:33.640
change the way something sounds.

00:06:33.760 --> 00:06:35.710
The way something sounds
when it's recorded,

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:38.640
or the way something sounds
before it actually gets recorded.

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:39.640
It really doesn't matter.

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:43.640
But these things can range from
simple things such as an equalizer,

00:06:43.730 --> 00:06:49.730
high, mid frequencies, low, mid, low end,
to compressors and noise gates,

00:06:49.820 --> 00:06:53.640
to modulation effects like chorusing,
flanging, and phasing,

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:56.580
to echo systems and delays,
all the way up to something

00:06:56.580 --> 00:06:58.640
maybe like a room simulator,
a reverb unit,

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:03.610
which can place an instrument or a
person's voice in any type of room.

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:05.630
It could be a concert hall,
it could be a church,

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:08.640
it could be a parking garage,
it could even be a hallway.

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:10.640
It could be a mall like this one.

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:12.640
And so that's the effects processors.

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:16.630
Now the nice thing is all of this
stuff that we've just looked at,

00:07:16.640 --> 00:07:18.630
the multitrack recorder,
the mixing console,

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:20.640
the effects processors,
with the exception of the microphone,

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:25.640
have all been rolled into one
production system called Logic Audio.

00:07:25.650 --> 00:07:29.640
And what we can do is we can go through
and look at some of the comparisons now.

00:07:29.850 --> 00:07:33.640
Logic Pro 6 really gives you
total integration in one package.

00:07:33.690 --> 00:07:38.640
And this has allowed
musicians and drummers,

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:41.870
and producers,
to freely experiment more with

00:07:41.940 --> 00:07:43.610
the music that they're recording.

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:46.790
In fact,
the whole workflow of recording music has

00:07:46.820 --> 00:07:50.480
somewhat changed because of computers,
because we can now do

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:52.640
things while we're doing,
while we're tracking,

00:07:52.640 --> 00:07:56.630
we can add EQ and we can add effects,
rather than waiting to the

00:07:56.660 --> 00:07:58.550
entire end of the process,
and just, "Okay, right,

00:07:58.590 --> 00:08:01.120
we're finished recording,
let's send it off to an overly

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:05.640
expensive guy to mix." So,
let's take a look at it.

00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:08.580
Logic Pro 6 as a multitrack
recorder for audio.

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:14.630
Now, Logic is only limited by the
audio hardware that you're using.

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:16.580
So, for example,
if you've got four inputs

00:08:16.580 --> 00:08:19.580
on your audio hardware,
that's the maximum amount of tracks

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:21.570
that you can record at any one time.

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:23.640
If you have 16 inputs,
that's the maximum amount of tracks

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:25.640
you can record at any one time.

00:08:25.640 --> 00:08:29.120
However,
Logic Pro 6 can play back up to 256

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:31.640
tracks of digital audio at any one time.

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:36.640
And that's with sample rates
all the way up to 192 kilohertz,

00:08:36.640 --> 00:08:38.640
at 24-bit, pristine sound.

00:08:38.640 --> 00:08:44.640
It also, like I say,
sample rates up to 192,

00:08:44.710 --> 00:08:47.640
and always sample accurate playback.

00:08:47.640 --> 00:08:50.640
The difference between Logic and
a regular multitrack is,

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:52.640
there's a little picture
here of the arrange window,

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:54.640
is that Logic is a multitrack
recorder for audio,

00:08:54.660 --> 00:08:57.600
but it's also a multitrack
recorder for MIDI.

00:08:57.730 --> 00:08:59.640
And for those of you who
are not familiar with MIDI,

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:02.640
MIDI stands for Musical Instrument
Digital Interface,

00:09:02.730 --> 00:09:06.640
and it's just a protocol
that allows synthesizers,

00:09:06.800 --> 00:09:09.640
let's say you've got a synthesizer
over here and one over here,

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:12.640
they allow them to talk and communicate.

00:09:12.640 --> 00:09:14.730
And inherently,
that allows the computer to

00:09:14.900 --> 00:09:16.640
communicate with an external keyboard.

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:19.640
So, for example,
when you're recording a MIDI keyboard,

00:09:19.680 --> 00:09:21.630
we refer to this as sequencing, actually.

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:26.580
So recording audio, multitracking,
recording MIDI, kind of sequencing,

00:09:26.580 --> 00:09:29.010
one of the same thing,
but we don't actually

00:09:29.010 --> 00:09:31.580
record an audio signal,
we record MIDI data.

00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:34.640
That MIDI data is played back
in real time out to the device,

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:39.430
which tells the device exactly which
notes and which chords to play.

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:42.640
And of course,
Logic offers non-destructive recording,

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:45.640
which is something that you
don't have in the analog world.

00:09:45.640 --> 00:09:48.780
If you accidentally hit record
over the last tail end of an

00:09:48.780 --> 00:09:51.020
amazing vocal performance,
you bet your bottom dollar

00:09:51.040 --> 00:09:55.640
that it will be gone for good,
and also can be very expensive.

00:09:55.640 --> 00:09:58.580
So, Logic Pro 6 has an
integrated mixing console.

00:09:58.670 --> 00:10:01.570
Logic Pro 6 has a beautiful
integrated mixing console.

00:10:01.670 --> 00:10:02.640
Every single channel that
can be recorded in it,

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:04.640
every single channel that
can be recorded in Logic,

00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:08.930
or played back, has its own mute button,
its own solo button for

00:10:08.970 --> 00:10:12.640
isolating it from the mix,
has a volume faders, and of course,

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:13.640
it has level meters.

00:10:13.640 --> 00:10:16.570
We also have many different
types of channel strips.

00:10:16.640 --> 00:10:19.640
We have audio channels,
we have auxiliary channels,

00:10:19.640 --> 00:10:23.640
we have buses, we have input channels,
we have output channels,

00:10:23.640 --> 00:10:25.610
just like in the analog world.

00:10:25.640 --> 00:10:30.640
Logic can operate every channel,
either mono, stereo,

00:10:30.640 --> 00:10:32.640
or incomplete surround.

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:34.640
Anyone out there mixing
music for surround,

00:10:34.800 --> 00:10:37.640
Logic Pro 6 is definitely the way to go.

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:41.640
It has flexible routing capabilities
and flexible DSP inserts.

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:44.640
In fact, let me just stray one second.

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:48.640
Thanks to the sheer power
of the G5 and the Macintosh,

00:10:48.640 --> 00:10:51.630
it's allowed Logic Pro 6 to
create a suite of unbelievable

00:10:51.630 --> 00:10:55.640
virtual instruments that can be
played like any other synthesizer,

00:10:55.640 --> 00:10:59.640
and they range from simple
sampled instruments,

00:10:59.790 --> 00:11:03.160
sampler, or sampled instruments,
to instruments that are

00:11:03.160 --> 00:11:06.200
created via synthesis,
and other instruments that are

00:11:06.200 --> 00:11:07.640
created via physical modeling.

00:11:07.640 --> 00:11:11.790
And they really allow the single
musician like myself or you to

00:11:11.790 --> 00:11:15.430
have many more textures and tones
available to you for when you're

00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:17.640
actually writing and arranging music.

